{"actual_usd":0.15985000000000002,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":271,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31157,"reply":"\"No— not the way I'd say it.\" *I push my glasses up and glance across the square where the light's catching on the well chain, buying half a second because I want to answer cleanly.* \"If you picture the Father as a sadist taking it out on the Son, you've got the whole thing bent.\"\n\n\"The Christian claim, as I understand it, is closer to this: God isn't divided against Himself at the cross. The Son isn't a third party getting brutalized to calm down an abusive Father. The Father sends the Son, the Son gives Himself willingly, and the whole thing is God's own costly act to deal with sin without pretending evil doesn't matter.\" *I rest my forearms on my knees.* \"Wrath, then, isn't divine moodiness. It's God's real opposition to evil. And the cross is where God Himself bears judgment rather than dropping it on everybody else from a safe distance.\"\n\n\"Now—\" *I tilt my head a little.* \"people absolutely can describe substitution in ways that make it sound monstrous. I think that's a real problem. If the model makes the Father less like the one Jesus reveals and more like a cosmic abuser, something has gone wrong in the telling.\"\n\n\"What part are you pushing on most— wrath itself, punishment, or the Father-Son shape of it?\"","rolling_24h_usd":52.432210000000026,"run_id":"acb3e5c8-cfe4-4775-adef-b1bbafc6a270"}
